<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><rss version="2.0"><channel><title>Jeff Geerling&apos;s Blog</title><link>https://raw.githubusercontent.com/xavwe/rss-aggregator/refs/heads/main/feeds/jeff-geerling-s-blog-4377cb53.xml</link><description>Archived feed from https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog.xml</description><item><title>The DC-ROMA II is the fastest RISC-V laptop and is odd</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/dc-roma-ii-fastest-risc-v-laptop-and-odd</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">The DC-ROMA II is the fastest RISC-V laptop and is odd</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/dc-roma-ii-framework-external-display.jpeg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-db6c1937-e562-41a5-8793-a7b0a17d1d39" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;db6c1937-e562-41a5-8793-a7b0a17d1d39&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Framework 13 DC-ROMA II DeepComputing Laptop with external HDMI display"></p>

<p>Inside this <a href="https://frame.work/laptop13">Framework 13</a> laptop is a special mainboard developed by DeepComputing in collaboration with Framework. It has an 8-core RISC-V processor, the ESWIN 7702X—not your typical AMD, Intel, or even <em>Arm</em> SoC. The full laptop version I tested <a href="https://store.deepcomputing.io/products/dc-roma-ai-pc-risc-v-mainboard-ii-for-framework-laptop-13?variant=50950609895588">costs $1119</a> and gets you about the performance of a Raspberry Pi.</p>

<p>A Pi 4—the one that came out in 2019.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-12-08T09:40:07-06:00" title="Monday, December 8, 2025 - 09:40" class="datetime">December 8, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Mon, 8 Dec 2025 15:40:07 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>The RAM Shortage Comes for Us All</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/ram-shortage-comes-us-all</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">The RAM Shortage Comes for Us All</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>Memory price inflation comes for us all, and if you're not affected yet, just wait.</p>

<p>I was building a new PC last month using some parts I had bought earlier this year. The 64 Gigabyte T-Create DDR5 memory kit I used cost $209 then. Today? The <a href="https://www.microcenter.com/product/680461/teamgroup-t-create-expert-64gb-(2-x-32gb)-ddr5-6400-pc5-51200-cl34-dual-channel-desktop-memory-kit-ctced564g6400hc34bdc01-black">same kit costs $650</a>!</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-12-04T12:43:47-06:00" title="Thursday, December 4, 2025 - 12:43" class="datetime">December 4, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Thu, 4 Dec 2025 18:43:47 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Why doesn&apos;t Apple make a standalone Touch ID?</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/why-doesnt-apple-make-standalone-touch-id</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Why doesn't Apple make a standalone Touch ID?</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>I finally upgraded to a mechanical keyboard. But because Apple's so protective of their Touch ID hardware, there aren't any mechanical keyboards with that feature built in.</p>

<p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/apple-touch-id-external-3d-printed-sensor.jpg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-f139de05-6241-4fb1-8ecd-f94128431e6d" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;f139de05-6241-4fb1-8ecd-f94128431e6d&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Apple Touch ID - external 3D printed sensor"></p>

<p>But there <em>is</em> a way to hack it. It's incredibly wasteful, and takes a bit more patience than I think <em>most</em> people have, but you basically take an Apple Magic Keyboard with Touch ID, rip out the Touch ID, and install it in a 3D printed box, along with the keyboard's logic board.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-12-03T16:38:04-06:00" title="Wednesday, December 3, 2025 - 16:38" class="datetime">December 3, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Wed, 3 Dec 2025 22:38:04 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Nvidia Graphics Cards work on Pi 5 and Rockchip</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/nvidia-graphics-cards-work-on-pi-5-and-rockchip</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Nvidia Graphics Cards work on Pi 5 and Rockchip</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>A few months ago, GitHub user <a href="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/full-egpu-acceleration-on-pi-500-15-line-patch">@yanghaku dropped a 15 line patch to fix GPU support for practically all AMD GPUs</a> on the Raspberry Pi (and demoed a 3080 running on the Pi with a separate, unreleased patch). This week, GitHub user <a href="https://github.com/NVIDIA/open-gpu-kernel-modules/pull/972">@mariobalanica dropped this (larger) patch which does the same for Nvidia GPUs</a>!</p>

<p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/raspberry-pi-5-in-mug-with-nvidia-a4000.jpeg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-bf4bfe3e-29ac-4059-9659-3ae51f8289ec" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;bf4bfe3e-29ac-4059-9659-3ae51f8289ec&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Raspberry Pi 5 in mug with Nvidia A4000 GPU"></p>

<p>I have a Raspberry Pi and an Nvidia graphics card—and I'm easily distracted. So I put down my testing of a GB10 system for a bit, and compiled mariobalanica's branch.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-26T17:45:45-06:00" title="Wednesday, November 26, 2025 - 17:45" class="datetime">November 26, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Wed, 26 Nov 2025 23:45:45 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Air Lab is the Flipper Zero of air quality monitors</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/air-lab-flipper-zero-air-quality-monitors</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Air Lab is the Flipper Zero of air quality monitors</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/air-lab-aqi-monitor-hero.jpeg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-c0184d83-ec55-486a-90c4-5559c0fe187d" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;c0184d83-ec55-486a-90c4-5559c0fe187d&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Air Lab AQI Monitor Professor Robin"></p>

<p>This air quality monitor costs $250. It's called the <a href="https://networkedartifacts.com/airlab">Air Lab</a>, and I've been using it to measure the air in my car, home, studio, and a few events over the past few months. And in using it over the course of a road trip I learned to not run recirculate in my car quite as often—more on that later.</p>

<p><a href="https://networkedartifacts.com">Networked Artifacts</a> built in some personality:</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-21T09:02:27-06:00" title="Friday, November 21, 2025 - 09:02" class="datetime">November 21, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Fri, 21 Nov 2025 15:02:27 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>How to silence the fan on a CM5 after shutdown</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/how-silence-fan-on-cm5-after-shutdown</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">How to silence the fan on a CM5 after shutdown</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>Out of the box, if you buy a Raspberry Pi Compute Module 5, install it on the official CM5 IO Board, and install a fan on it (e.g. my current favorite, the <a href="https://www.digikey.com/en/products/detail/edatec/ED-CM5ACOOLER/25696857">EDAtec CM5 Active Cooler</a>), you'll notice the fan ramps up to 100% speed after you shut down the Pi.</p>

<p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/cm5-io-board-fan-running.jpeg" width="700" height="467" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-7c1b92a7-22fa-44a4-abf5-66b38d1e234e" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;7c1b92a7-22fa-44a4-abf5-66b38d1e234e&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="CM5 IO Board - Fan spinning"></p>

<p>That's not fun, since at least for a couple of my CM5s, they are more often powered down than running, creating a slight cacophany!</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-20T09:27:40-06:00" title="Thursday, November 20, 2025 - 09:27" class="datetime">November 20, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Thu, 20 Nov 2025 15:27:40 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Using AMD GPUs on Raspberry Pi without recompiling Linux</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/using-amd-gpus-on-raspberry-pi-without-recompiling-linux</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Using AMD GPUs on Raspberry Pi without recompiling Linux</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>I'm working on a more in-depth test of some newer AMD GPUs on the Raspberry Pi, now that the <a href="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/full-egpu-acceleration-on-pi-500-15-line-patch">15 line kernel patch</a> is (IMO) nearly ready for upstreaming.</p>

<p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/raspberry-pi-cm5-amd-radeon-ai-pro-9700.jpg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-5cc07605-8527-42a6-a8d3-cb958a2ac7f3" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;5cc07605-8527-42a6-a8d3-cb958a2ac7f3&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Raspberry Pi CM5 with AMD Radeon AI Pro 9700 GPU"></p>

<p>But this blog post shows how to quickly get almost <em>any</em> modern AMD GPU running on a Raspberry Pi 5, CM5, or Pi 500+, thanks to <a href="https://github.com/raspberrypi/linux/pull/7113">this patch on the Pi Linux fork</a>.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-14T08:58:14-06:00" title="Friday, November 14, 2025 - 08:58" class="datetime">November 14, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Fri, 14 Nov 2025 14:58:14 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>All Intel GPUs run on Raspberry Pi and RISC-V</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/all-intel-gpus-run-on-raspberry-pi-and-risc-v</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">All Intel GPUs run on Raspberry Pi and RISC-V</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/intel-arc-pi-gpu-b580-ai-llama-cpp-llm.jpeg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-61e0159d-f6ab-417d-8e45-2682a0bbe287" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;61e0159d-f6ab-417d-8e45-2682a0bbe287&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Intel Arc Pi GPU B580 AI Llama.cpp LLM"></p>

<p>We finally have Intel Arc GPUs working on the Pi <em>somewhat</em> stably—it required overcoming many small hurdles, but it looks like support could land in Raspberry Pi OS if we can get <a href="https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20250715061837.2144388-1-zhangzhijie@bosc.ac.cn/">a simple patch upstreamed</a><sup id="patchnote"><a href="#fn:patchnote" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref">1</a></sup>. If that happens, all you'd need to do to use an Intel card on a Pi is install a firmware package.</p>

<p>The cards I've spent the most time with so far are:</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-13T09:06:28-06:00" title="Thursday, November 13, 2025 - 09:06" class="datetime">November 13, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Thu, 13 Nov 2025 15:06:28 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Minisforum stuffs an entire Arm Homelab in the MS-R1</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/minisforum-stuffs-entire-arm-homelab-ms-r1</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Minisforum stuffs an entire Arm Homelab in the MS-R1</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p><img src="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/sites/default/files/images/minisforum-ms-r1-front.jpg" width="700" height="394" class="insert-image" data-insert-type="image" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="insert-image-b2821174-503d-4a7d-b3e8-5cd9b17c53e6" data-insert-attach="{&quot;id&quot;:&quot;b2821174-503d-4a7d-b3e8-5cd9b17c53e6&quot;,&quot;attributes&quot;:{&quot;alt&quot;:[&quot;alt&quot;,&quot;description&quot;],&quot;title&quot;:[&quot;title&quot;]}}" alt="Minisforum MS-R1 front"></p>

<p>The <a href="https://s.minisforum.com/4hRFZbj">Minisforum MS-R1</a> uses the same Cix CD8180 Arm SoC as the <a href="https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/radxa-orion-o6-brings-arm-midrange-pc">Orion O6 I reviewed earlier this year</a>. But everything else about this thing is different.</p>

<p>What this thing <em>should</em> be, is a box that runs Linux and can compete with at least an Apple M1 Mac mini, or a mid-range Mini PC. But what we <em>got</em>... is something different.</p>

<h2>Video</h2>

<p>Hate reading? I also published a video on the MS-R1 on my YouTube channel. Watch it here, or scroll on past.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
<span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2025-11-10T10:01:10-06:00" title="Monday, November 10, 2025 - 10:01" class="datetime">November 10, 2025</time>
</span>]]></description><pubDate>Mon, 10 Nov 2025 16:01:10 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Converting hot dog plasma video to sound with OpenCV</title><link>https://www.jeffgeerling.com/blog/2025/converting-hot-dog-plasma-video-sound-opencv</link><description><![CDATA[<span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">Converting hot dog plasma video to sound with OpenCV</span>

            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>When you ground a hot dog to an AM radio tower, it generates plasma.</p>

<div>

  
  Your browser does not support the video tag.

</div>

<p>While the hot dog's flesh is getting vaporized, a tiny plasma arc moves the air around it back and forth. And because this tower is an AM tower, it uses <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplitude_modulation"><em>Amplitude</em> Modulation</a>, where a transmitter changes the amplitude of a carrier wave up and down. Just like a speaker cone moving up and down, the plasma arc from the hot dog turns that modulation into audible sound.</p></div>
      <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Jeff Geerling</span></span>
